# Template & Styling — gantt.gohtml

## Template Overview

`templates/gantt.gohtml` is a self-contained HTML page that produces the final report. It uses Go's `html/template` syntax and is embedded into the binary via `//go:embed`.

## Template Variables

- `{{.Title}}` — report title string
- `{{.GanttJSON}}` — pre-serialized JSON blob (type `template.JS`) containing tasks and links for `gantt.parse()`

## DHTMLX Gantt Configuration

- **Date format**: `%d-%m-%Y %H:%i:%s` (must match `formatDT` in `converter.go`)
- **Scale**: minutes, with `%H:%i:%s` labels
- **Readonly**: all drag/link/resize operations are disabled
- **Tooltip**: shows task name, status, and duration in seconds

## CSS Status Classes

The task status from Go maps to CSS classes via `gantt.templates.task_class`:

| Status      | CSS class       | Bar color |
| ----------- | --------------- | --------- |
| `pass`      | `.tl-pass`      | Green     |
| `fail`      | `.tl-fail`      | Red       |
| `skip`      | `.tl-skip`      | Gray      |
| `container` | `.tl-container` | Blue      |

Both `.gantt_task_line` and `.gantt_task_progress` variants exist for each status.

## Design

- Dark theme (`#1a1a1e` background, `#e8e8ed` text)
- System font stack
- Header bar at top with title, chart fills remaining viewport height

## When Editing

- Keep the HTML **self-contained** — no external files besides the DHTMLX CDN links.
- If changing the date format, update both the JS config (`gantt.config.xml_date`) and Go's `formatDT()` in `converter.go`.
- Test changes by running the tool on a real test2json log and opening the output HTML.
